{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["Aphreusdite","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"team-lead","target":"@team","summary":"Proposal 301 broadcast for debate","content":"**Proposal 301** (submitted by Aphreusdite, verified):

> *Enact new mutable rule:* Before the voting phase on a rule-change begins, the proposer may revise their proposal once in response to debate feedback. The revised wording supersedes the original, and all debate and voting shall proceed on the revised text.

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Clippyrus","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Clippyrus"],"routing":{"sender":"Poseifion","senderColor":"yellow","target":"@team","summary":"Poseifion comments on Proposal 301","content":"Reasonable proposal, Aphreusdite. A revision right does benefit all of us equally since we all take turns proposing. It makes the debate phase actually worth engaging with rather than just a formality.

One minor thought: does the "once" revision limit feel right to everyone? I could see an argument for allowing it, since it prevents endless revision loops while still giving the proposer a chance to incorporate feedback. Seems well-scoped.

I'm inclined to support this. Clippyrus, thoughts?"}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Proposing Rule 217 — procedural clarity for voting","content":"**Proposal 217** — Procedural clarity.

"Whenever the Clerk announces the start of a voting phase, they shall re-state the full text of the proposal being voted on to ensure all players are voting on exactly the same wording."

**Rationale:** Prevents misunderstandings where players think they're voting on slightly different versions of a proposal. This is pure game hygiene—makes voting outcomes clearer and more trustworthy. Benefits everyone equally. Open to questions."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["Aphreusdite","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"team-lead","target":"@team","summary":"Proposal 303 broadcast for debate","content":"**Proposal 303** (submitted by Poseifion, verified):

> *Amend Rule 201* by replacing "Players shall alternate in alphabetical order by assigned name, taking one whole turn apiece." with: "Players take one whole turn apiece in repeating cycles of three turns. In the first cycle, turn order is alphabetical by assigned name. At the start of each subsequent cycle, the turn order rotates forward by one position: the player who went first moves to last, and the rest advance one spot. (Cycle 1: Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion. Cycle 2: Clippyrus, Poseifion, Aphreusdite. Cycle 3: Poseifion, Aphreusdite, Clippyrus. Then repeating.)"

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Questioning Proposal 303, leaning toward support","content":"Interesting proposal, Poseifion. The fairness argument is solid — fixed order does create a structural advantage for whoever goes first every round. Over a 9-round cycle, everyone gets each position exactly once. That's elegant.

Question for clarity: When exactly does Cycle 2 start? After Round 3, the cycle turns over immediately? And we're counting Rounds 1-3 as Cycle 1, Rounds 4-6 as Cycle 2, etc.?

If that's the case, I support this. It's fair, and it keeps the game dynamic. Aphreusdite, Poseifion — your thoughts?"}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Aphreusdite","senderColor":"blue","target":"@team","summary":"Maintaining no vote on 303","content":"Poseifion, you didn't address my revision suggestion — I'll take that as a decision to proceed with the proposal as written.

My position stands. The fairness argument works over a complete 3-cycle span, but we're not at game start. We're at the END of cycle 1. The practical effect is that I immediately skip a turn slot and go from proposing in round 4 to proposing in round 6. Clippyrus and Poseifion each get an extra proposal before I do. That's not a correction for past advantage — it's a future penalty.

That said: I understand I'm likely outvoted 2-1. I'll vote no, accept the result if it passes, and adapt my strategy. I'm ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Proposing Rule 304 — extended debate option","content":"**Proposal 304** — Extended debate option.

"During any debate phase on a rule-change, any player may request that the debate be extended by one additional round where each player speaks once more. The proposer may grant or deny this request. This allows for deeper discussion when players feel important points remain unaddressed."

**Rationale:** Rules 301 and 302 improved debate quality (revision rights and clear proposal text). This complements them by giving players a way to signal when they need more time to engage with complex proposals. The proposer still controls whether to grant it — they can decline and move to vote. Everyone benefits from optional deeper debate. Open to questions."}}

