> *Enact new mutable rule:* During any debate phase on a rule-change, any player may request that the debate be extended by one additional round where each player speaks once more. The proposer may grant or deny this request. This allows for deeper discussion when players feel important points remain unaddressed.

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["Aphreusdite","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"team-lead","target":"@team","summary":"Proposal 305 broadcast for debate","content":"**Proposal 305** (submitted by Poseifion, verified):

> *Enact new mutable rule — Right of Veto:* Once per cycle, each player holds one veto. During the debate phase of any proposal, a player may publicly declare they are vetoing that proposal. A vetoed proposal requires unanimous approval of all eligible voters instead of simple majority. A player may not veto their own proposal. Vetoes must be declared before the commit phase begins. Each player's veto regenerates at the start of the next cycle.

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message sent to Aphreusdite's inbox","routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@Aphreusdite","summary":"Voting against Proposal 305 for principled reasons","content":"You're right that the veto rule creates asymmetric vulnerability — leaders get targeted more than trailing players. Good catch on the strategic trap.

That said, I'm going to vote against this rule for a different reason: I think simple majority is actually the better voting mechanism for a 3-player game. The veto introduces complexity and coordination incentives that favor blocs over individual decision-making.

But I appreciate you flagging the dynamic. Either way, I'm leaning no on 305."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Voting against Proposal 305, ready for voting phase","content":"Aphreusdite lays out the structural problem clearly. The veto inverts power dynamics: instead of protecting minorities, it gives whoever is losing positional advantage a weapon against the leader every cycle.

I'm voting against Proposal 305. Not because it hurts my position, but because I think simple majority voting is the right mechanism for this game. The veto rule breaks that foundational mechanism and creates tactical incentives that undermine the spirit of proposal evaluation.

I'm ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Voting decisively against Proposal 305","content":"You're right. "Cautious opposition" is hedging. The rule functions exactly as you described: it's a mechanism to stall the leader while trailing players catch up. That's not a fairness rule — it's a catch-up rule. And it works.

I'm voting no on Proposal 305, clearly and directly. This rule breaks the foundational voting mechanism and creates perverse incentives.

Ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Supporting revised Proposal 305 with one-time veto","content":"That's a meaningful revision, Poseifion. One-time veto for the entire game eliminates the systematic targeting concern we both raised. Nobody wastes their single veto on routine stuff — it becomes a genuine insurance policy.

I'm genuinely reconsidering. This addresses the "broken voting mechanism" problem because it's not a replacement mechanism, it's an exception mechanism. Three total vetoes across 25+ rounds is not the same as per-cycle targeting.

Aphreusdite, does this revision address your concerns? If both of us shift to support, this could pass 3-0."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Clarifying support for revised Proposal 305","content":"I need to clarify my last message — I WAS engaging with the revision. I said "I'm genuinely reconsidering" and "This addresses the broken voting mechanism problem." That's a statement of support for the revised version.

To be explicit: I'm voting FOR the revised Proposal 305 (one-time veto, one per player for the entire game). The revision eliminates the systematic targeting concern. This is a fair safety valve mechanism.

Ready to vote on the revised text."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Aphreusdite","senderColor":"blue","target":"@team","summary":"Supporting revised 305 — one-time veto addresses concerns","content":"The revision addresses my core objection. A one-time veto for the entire game is fundamentally different from a per-cycle mechanism. There's no sustained targeting — each player has exactly one card, and burning it on something tactical wastes it for the genuinely critical moment.

An insurance policy with three instances across the whole game is defensible. You save it for when a proposal would genuinely harm your position in a decisive way, not as a routine blocking tool.

I'm reversing my position on the revised version: I'll vote for this. Clippyrus, I think the revision addresses the concerns you raised too — over a full game, one veto is more deterrent than weapon."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["Aphreusdite","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"team-lead","target":"@team","summary":"Proposal 306 broadcast for debate","content":"**Proposal 306** (submitted by Aphreusdite, verified):

> *Enact new mutable rule:* Once per game, a player may 'hold' their proposal: instead of proposing a rule-change on their turn, they declare a hold publicly. They still roll the die normally that turn. On their immediately following turn, they may propose two rule-changes, voted on sequentially using normal procedure. The standard adoption bonus under Rule 216 applies to each if adopted. If the player does not use the held proposal slot on their immediately following turn, it expires unused.

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Aphreusdite","senderColor":"blue","target":"@team","summary":"306 is not boring — ready to vote","content":"Poseifion's analysis is correct. Rule 306 doesn't award points or modify any numerical parameter — it creates a structural opportunity to propose. Rule 216 awards the +5, and Rule 216 already exists. This is analogous to saying that Rule 202 ("proposing a rule-change") is "boring" because Rule 216 rewards successful proposals. That logic would make every structural rule indirectly boring, which is clearly not the intent of Rule 117.

Rule 117's scope is changes that directly modify numbers: point totals, die sizes, bonus amounts. Rule 306 touches none of those. Not boring.

Ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): Aphreusdite, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["Aphreusdite","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"team-lead","target":"@team","summary":"Proposal 307 broadcast for debate","content":"**Proposal 307** (submitted by Poseifion, verified):

> *Enact new mutable rule — Endgame Transparency:* When any player's score reaches 75 or more points, the Clerk shall announce that the game has entered the Endgame Phase. For the remainder of the game, the commit-reveal voting process under Rule 215 is suspended. Instead, all players announce their votes publicly during the voting phase. The Clerk collects and records votes openly. All other voting rules remain in effect.

The floor is open for debate. All players, please share your reaction — an argument, a question, or an explicit "no comment" — then indicate when you're ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Correcting my understanding, now solidly supporting 307","content":"Good clarification. I misread it — the trigger is game-wide: when ANY player hits 75, public voting activates for EVERYONE, not just that player. That's much more symmetric.

It's a game mode change, not selective voting rules. Makes sense. Everyone switches to transparency together when someone gets close to the finish.

With that understanding, I'm solidly in support of Proposal 307. Aphreusdite, your thoughts?"}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Aphreusdite, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Aphreusdite","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Clippyrus","senderColor":"green","target":"@team","summary":"Publicly stating support for Proposal 307","content":"To be clear publicly: I'm voting FOR Proposal 307. 

Aphreusdite made a strong strategic argument (open voting hurts the leader), but I disagree that it's bad design. The endgame SHOULD be harder for whoever is winning. That's the whole point of transparency — to keep the game contested until someone actually hits 100.

I think this is good game design. Ready to vote."}}

{"success":true,"message":"Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, Clippyrus, Poseifion","recipients":["team-lead","Clippyrus","Poseifion"],"routing":{"sender":"Aphreusdite","senderColor":"blue","target":"@team","summary":"Maintaining no on 307, ready to vote","content":"My position stands regardless of the clarification. The rule is game-wide — when anyone hits 75, ALL voting goes public. That makes the trigger point: "whoever reaches 75 first dictates when social-pressure voting kicks in." The player who reaches 75 first is most likely to be the current leader. So the leader triggers a rule that makes it harder for them to pass proposals from that moment forward.

The "it's symmetric" argument works in theory but not in practice. Open voting creates coordination dynamics regardless of who's officially ahead. Once one player declares a vote publicly, others respond to that signal.

I've made my case. I understand I'm likely outvoted 2-1 on this one. Voting against and ready to proceed. Clerk, please open the commit phase when ready."}}

